            <entry xml:id="entry_cʼaj" xml:lang="os">
                <form type="lemma"><orth>cʼaj</orth></form>
                <sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>колодец</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>well</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Слово идет из персидского через грузинское посредство. Ср.
                        <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>čāh</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>čʼa</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/>
                        <w>čʼa</w>
                        <gloss><q>колодец</q></gloss></mentioned>. Персидское <mentioned
                        xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>čāh</w></mentioned> восходит к <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/>
                        <w>*čāϑa-(čāta-)</w></mentioned>), которое сохранилось в осетинском как
                    старое иранское наследие, но со значением ‘озеро’: <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_cad"/>. Таким образом, %icʼaj%i и <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_cad"/> представляют исторически одно и то же слово, хотя это
                    сейчас уже не осознается. Ср. в этом отношении слова <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_ax0yr"/> и <ref type="xr" target="#entry_zian"/> и <ref
                        type="xr" target="#entry_zyn"/>. Ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_cad"
                            />.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope
                            xml:lang="ru">51 прим., 519</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">51
                            footnote., 519</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">The word comes from Persian through Georgian. Cf. <mentioned
                        xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>čāh</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>čʼa</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sva"><lang/>
                        <w>čʼa</w>
                        <gloss><q>well</q></gloss></mentioned>. Persian <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>čāh</w></mentioned> traces back to <mentioned xml:lang="ira"><lang/>
                        <w>*čāϑa-(čāta-)</w></mentioned>) which is found in Ossetic as an old
                    Iranian heritage but with the meaning ‘lake’: <ref type="xr" target="#entry_cad"
                    />. Thus, %icʼaj%i and <ref type="xr" target="#entry_cad"/> historically
                    represent the same word, although nowadays it is not realized. Cf. in that
                    respect the following words: <ref type="xr" target="#entry_ax0yr"/> and <ref
                        type="xr" target="#entry_zian"/> and <ref type="xr" target="#entry_zyn"/>.
                    Cf. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_cad"/>.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope xml:lang="ru">51 прим.,
                            519</biblScope><biblScope xml:lang="en">51 footnote.,
                        519</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
